  "doc_id": "38998",
  "text": "Some studies suggest a different role for GITR in CD4 + and CD8 + cells. During the activation process of CD4 + CD25 -cells, GITR upregulation is mainly dependent on CD28 co-triggering as demonstrated by the greatly increased expression of GITR after CD28-co-triggering and substantial inhibition of GITR upregulation upon activation when physiological CD28 engagement was inhibited by anti-CD80/86 Abs [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Of note, GITR expression is upregulated by CD28 activation also in the absence of TCR triggering [CITATION_3] , suggesting that a specific signal, not correlated with activation/proliferation, departs from CD28. As a consequence, when CD28 triggering is impeded, the costimulatory effect of GITR-triggering is decreased [CITATION_4] . Kohm et al. demonstrated that this effect is dependent on CD28-driven IL-2 production [CITATION_5] , while Stephens et al. demonstrated that it is independent of this cytokine [CITATION_6] . However, the latter used CD4 + CD25 -cells while the former used total CD4 + cells. In conclusion, it seems that, in CD4 + cells, GITR expression and signalling follows CD28 signalling and probably GITR should be regarded as one of the pathways activated by CD28 activation.",
